folder: Greenwich Street & Christopher Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Clearing, 1-7 Christopher Street at the N.W. corner of Greenwich Avenue (right). A new apartment building is to be erected. Nos. 1 to 7 Christopher Street and 3-13 Greenwich Avenue were demolished for its site. No. 15 Greenwich Avenue, an old fourstory brick house, was not carefully shored up when No. 13 was demolished, and conseguently collapsed. For some years following
its site will remain vacant.
October 13, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
No. 1 (1-7) Christopher Street, the completed building, beginning ita first season, a year later, seen across the parking space at the S.W. corner where 1-5 Greenwich Avenue and 2-6 Christopher Street used to stand. TThe view at the right is northwest straight
up Greenwich Avenue.
October 3, 1931.
P. L. Sporr.

folder: Christopher Street & Greenwich Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Christopher Street, south side, from No. 178 Christopher, east of West to Greenwich Streets, showing the demolition of the old houses adjoining and at the S.W. corner of Washington Street. The Barrow Street garage, the Christopher Street wing of which was at 174-168 Christopher Street, has also been demolished, and is to be replaced by a new garage for the Parmelee Transportation Company (the Yellow Cabs).
The Federal Building, with its post office, customs offices, and other federal agencies, is the tall building occupying the entire block bounded by Christopher, Washington, Barrow and Greenwich Streets.

July 25, 1930

P.L. Sperr.

folder: Greenwich Street & Christopher Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Greenwich Street, north from Christopher Street. Shown are details of the Christopher Street station and the tracks of the old 9th Avenue Elevated Line. The photographer's vantage point
is the uptown local platform.
May 7, 1940
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr
No.I3)
A view under the Elevated Lines showing pavement conditions. The generating plant on the right bears No. 683. At the left margin is a business building numbered 692. This location was verified by personal observation. 9-26-40
June 2, 1937
W. P. A. photo
Five Boroughs Project
